  "text": "The primary source of audit logging for authorization decisions in Apache Kafka is the `StandardAuthorizerData` class located at `metadata/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/metadata/authorizer/StandardAuthorizerData.java`. This class contains two critical methods for audit logging:\n\n1. **logAuditMessage()** (line 281-310): This method logs authorization decisions using a logger named 'kafka.authorizer.logger'. It handles both ALLOWED and DENIED results with appropriate log levels:\n   - For ALLOWED results: logs at debug level if `action.logIfAllowed()` is true (indicating actual access was granted), otherwise logs at trace level\n   - For DENIED results: logs at info level if `action.logIfDenied()` is true (indicating an explicit denial of requested access), otherwise logs at trace level\n\n2. **buildAuditMessage()** (line 254-271): This method constructs detailed audit messages containing:\n   - Principal (user) making the request\n   - Authorization decision (Allowed or Denied)\n   - Operation requested\n   - Client host address\n   - Resource details (type, pattern, name)\n   - Request type\n   - Resource reference count\n   - Matching ACL rule\n\nThe `StandardAuthorizer` class (line 145-156) implements the `authorize()` method that delegates authorization decisions to `StandardAuthorizerData.authorize()`, which in turn calls `logAuditMessage()` for each action.\n\nSupporting classes include:\n- `Action.java`: Contains `logIfAllowed()` and `logIfDenied()` flags (lines 70, 82) that control whether specific authorization decisions should be logged\n- `AuthorizationResult.java`: Defines the ALLOWED and DENIED enum values\n\nThe audit logging system in Kafka integrates with the authorization flow through the Action object parameters, which specify logging flags passed through `AuthHelper.scala` helper methods that call the authorizer with appropriate flags based on the context of each authorization request."
